'''Scarlett Johansson''' (born November 22, 1984) is an American actress and singer. Johansson made her film debut in the 1994 film ''[[North (film)|North]]'' and was later nominated for the [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Female Lead]] for her performance in 1996's ''[[Manny & Lo]]''. Johansson rose to fame with her roles in 1998's ''[[The Horse Whisperer]]'' and 2001's ''[[Ghost World (film)|Ghost World]]''.

She transitioned to adult roles with her performances in [[Sofia Coppola]]'s ''[[Lost in Translation (film)|Lost in Translation]]'', for which she won a [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role|B.A.F.T.A. Award]], and ''[[Girl with a Pearl Earring (film)|Girl with a Pearl Earring]]'', both of which earned her [[Golden Globe Award]] nominations in 2003. A role in ''[[A Love Song for Bobby Long]]'' earned her a third [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress&nbsp;<U+2013> Motion Picture Drama|Golden Globe for Best Actress]] nomination. Following an appearance in ''[[The Island (2005 film)|The Island]]'', Johansson garnered a fourth Golden Globe nomination, for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress&nbsp;<U+2013> Motion Picture|Best Supporting Actress]], for her role in [[Woody Allen]]'s ''[[Match Point]]''. She followed that with another Allen film, ''[[Scoop (2006 film)|Scoop]]'', with [[Hugh Jackman]]. A role in [[Brian De Palma]]'s [[film noir]] ''[[The Black Dahlia (film)|The Black Dahlia]]'' was followed by a second role opposite Hugh Jackman in ''[[The Prestige (film)|The Prestige]]'', also starring [[Christian Bale]].

On May 20, 2008, Johansson debuted as a vocalist on her first album, ''[[Anywhere I Lay My Head]]'', which included [[cover version]]s of [[Tom Waits]] songs. Her second album, ''[[Break Up (Scarlett Johansson and Pete Yorn album)|Break Up]]'', with [[Pete Yorn]] was released in September 2009.

== Early life ==
Johansson was born in New York City on November 22, 1984.<ref name="people"/> Her father, Karsten Johansson, is a Danish architect who was the son of Ejner Johansson, a screen-writer and director. Her mother, Melanie Sloan, a producer, comes from an [[Ashkenazi]] Jewish family from [[the Bronx]].<ref name="ashref">{{cite news |title=Scarlett Johansson's a Jew, too |url=http://jta.org/news/article/2008/03/23/107668/johanssonportman |publisher=JTA |date=March 23, 2008 |accessdate=March 23, 2008}}</ref><ref name="heritage">{{cite web |title=A period film made by someone who hates period films{{ndash}} [[Peter Webber]] on [[Girl with a Pearl Earring]] |work=Neil Young's Film Lounge |date=January 6, 2004 |accessdate=April 12, 2006 |first=Neil |last=Young |url=http://www.jigsawlounge.co.uk/film/peterwebberinterview.html}}</ref><ref name="parade">{{cite news |title=More Than A Pretty Face |work=Parade |first=James |last=Kaplan |url=http://www.parade.com/export/sites/default/articles/editions/2007/edition_03-11-2007/Scarlett_Johansson |date=March 11, 2007}}</ref><ref name="esquire">{{cite news |title=Scarlett Johansson Is the Sexiest Woman Alive, 2006 |url=http://www.esquire.com/women/the-sexiest-woman-alive/scarlett-johansson-pics |work=Esquire |first=A.J. |last=Jacobs |date=October 31, 2006}}</ref> Johansson's parents met in Denmark, where her mother lived with Johansson's maternal grandmother, Dorothy, a former bookkeeper and schoolteacher.<ref name="grandma">{{cite news |work=The Jewish Forward |first=Anthony |last=Weiss |title=The Scarlett Grandma |url=http://www.forward.com/articles/the-scarlett-grandma/ | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080120002634/http://www.forward.com/articles/the-scarlett-grandma/ |archivedate=January 20, 2008 |accessdate=April 12, 2006 |date=April 7, 2006}}</ref> Johansson has an older sister, [[Vanessa Johansson|Vanessa]], who is an actress; an older brother, Adrian; a twin brother, Hunter (who appeared in the film ''[[Manny & Lo]]'' with Scarlett);<ref>{{IMDb name|0423956|name=Hunter Johansson}}</ref> and an older half-brother, Christian, from her father's first marriage.<ref name=recordd>{{cite news|last=Millar|first=John|coauthors=|title=MY ROLL IN THE HAY WITH JONATHAN WAS AGONY|pages=|publisher=Daily Record|date=2005-12-22|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/tm_objectid=16511119&method=full&siteid=66633&headline=my-roll-in-the-hay-with-jonathan-was-agony--name_page.html|accessdate=2010-05-07}}</ref>

Johansson grew up in a house-hold with "little money,"<ref name="parade" /> and with a mother who was a "film buff."<ref name="localfav" /> She and her brother, Hunter, attended P.S. 41 in [[Greenwich Village]] in elementary school.<ref>{{cite news |title=Scoopy's Notebook |work=The Villager |url=http://www.thevillager.com/villager_268/scoopysnotebook.html |volume=78 |number=3 |date=June 18, 2008 |accessdate=July 28, 2009}}</ref> Johansson began her theatrical training by attending and graduating from [[Professional Children's School]] in [[Manhattan]] in 2002.<ref>{{cite web |title=Distinguished Alumni |url=http://www.pcs-nyc.org/subpage.cfm?tbl=1&sct=26#theater |publisher=Professional Children's School |accessdate=July 28, 2009}}</ref>

== Acting career ==
=== Early roles ===
Johansson began acting during childhood, after her mother started taking her to auditions.<ref name="parade" /> She made her film debut at nine years old, as [[John Ritter]]'s daughter in the 1994 fantasy comedy ''[[North (film)|North]]''.<ref name="people">{{cite web |title=Scarlett Johansson Biography |url=http://www.people.com/people/scarlett_johansson/biography/0,,,00.html |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |accessdate=July 26, 2009}}</ref> Following minor roles in the 1995 film ''[[Just Cause (film)|Just Cause]]'', as the daughter of [[Sean Connery]] and [[Kate Capshaw]], and ''[[If Lucy Fell]]'' in 1996, she played the role of Amanda in ''[[Manny & Lo]]'' (1996). Her performance in ''Manny & Lo'' garnered a nomination for the [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Lead Female]],<ref name="people" /> and positive reviews, one noting, "[the film] grows on you, largely because of the charm of ... Scarlett Johansson",<ref>{{cite news |title=Many things to like about "Manny & Lo' |first=Barbara |last=Shulgasser |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/e/a/1996/08/09/WEEKEND6031.dtl |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |date=August 9, 1996 |accessdate=July 26, 2009}}</ref> while ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' critic [[Mick LaSalle]] commentated on her "peaceful aura", and wrote, "If she can get through puberty with that aura undisturbed, she could become an important actress."<ref>{{cite news |title=Two Girls, a Condo and One Kidnapped Mom |work=San Francisco Chronicle |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/1996/08/09/DD66424.DTL |date=August 9, 1996 |accessdate=July 26, 2009 | first=Mick | last=Lasalle}}</ref>

After appearing in minor roles in ''Fall'' and ''[[Home Alone 3]]'' in 1997, Johansson garnered widely spread attention for her performance in the 1998 film ''[[The Horse Whisperer]]'', directed by [[Robert Redford]].<ref name="people" /> She received a nomination for the [[Chicago Film Critics Association|Chicago Film Critics Association Award for Most Promising Actress]] for the film.<ref name="CFCA CS-T">{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=CSTB&p_theme=cstb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB423E8C6BDEF67&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=Chicago critics list best films|date=January 19, 1999|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|accessdate=1 August 2010}}</ref><ref name="IMDB-Awards">{{cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0424060/awards|title=Scarlett Johansson&nbsp;<U+2014> Awards|publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]]|accessdate=1 August 2010}}</ref> In 1999, she appeared in both ''[[My Brother the Pig]]'' and the [[neo-noir]] [[Coen brothers]] film ''[[The Man Who Wasn't There]]''. Also in 1999, she appeared in the music video for [[Mandy Moore]]'s single, "[[Candy (Mandy Moore song)|Candy]]".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,488747,00.html |title='He's Just Not That Into You' Cast: Then & Now |publisher=Fox News |date=February 6, 2009 |accessdate=July 26, 2009}}</ref> Although the film was not a box office success,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=ghostworld.htm |title=Ghost World |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=July 28, 2009}}</ref> she received praise for her break-out role<ref>{{cite news |title=Scarlett Johansson&nbsp;<U+2013> 'Ghost World' |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=July 28, 2009 |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/music/la-et-bio-sjohansson-pg,0,7027798.photogallery}}</ref> in the 2001 film, ''[[Ghost World (film)|Ghost World]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ghost World (2001) |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/ghost_world/ |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=July 28, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/video/titles/ghostworld |title=Ghost World |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=July 28, 2009}}</ref> Credited with "sensitivity and talent [that] belie her age",<ref>{{cite news |first=Marjorie |last=Baumgarten |title=Ghost World |work=[[Austin Chronicle]] |url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/gyrobase/Calendar/Film?Film=oid%3A141399 |date=August 24, 2001 |accessdate=July 28, 2009}}</ref> Johansson went on to win the [[Chlotrudis Award for Best Supporting Actress|Chlotrudis]]<ref>{{cite web |title=2002, 8th Annual Awards |publisher=Chlotrudis Society for Independent Films |url=http://www.chlotrudis.org/awards/archives/eighth/index.html |accessdate=July 28, 2009}}</ref> and [[Toronto Film Critics Association Award for Best Supporting Actress|Toronto Film Critics Association Awards for Best Supporting Actress]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://torontofilmcritics.com/blog/2001/12/21/tfca-awards-2001/ |title=TFCA Awards 2001 |date=December 21, 2001 |publisher=Toronto Film Critics Association |accessdate=July 28, 2009}}</ref> and was nominated for the [[Online Film Critics Society Award for Best Supporting Actress]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ofcs.rottentomatoes.com/pages/awards/2001nominees |title=OFCS Awards for 2001 Nominees |publisher=Online Film Critics Society |accessdate=July 28, 2009}}</ref> In 2002, Johansson appeared in the comedy-horror thriller ''[[Eight Legged Freaks]]'', starring [[David Arquette]].

=== Transition to adult roles ===
Johansson made the transition from teen roles to adult roles, with two such roles in 2003.<ref name="UtusanAdultRoles">{{cite web|url=http://www.utusan.com.my/utusan/info.asp?y=2003&dt=0906&pub=Utusan_Express&sec=Entertainment&pg=en_10.htm|title=Toronto film fest puts on the ritz with promising movie lineup|date=June 9, 2003|publisher=[[Utusan Malaysia]]|accessdate=21 May 2010}}</ref> In the [[Sofia Coppola]] film ''[[Lost in Translation (film)|Lost in Translation]]'', she played Charlotte, an abandoned young wife, opposite [[Bill Murray]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Lost in Translation |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/lostintranslation |accessdate=July 29, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Lost in Translation (2003) |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/lost_in_translation/ |accessdate=July 29, 2009}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] wrote that he loved the film and described the performances of Johansson and Murray as "wonderful."<ref>{{cite news |last=Ebert |first=Roger |title=Lost in Translation |work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=September 12, 2003 |url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20030912/REVIEWS/309120302/1023 |accessdate=July 29, 2009}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' wrote of Johansson's "embracing, restful serenity,"<ref>{{cite news |last=Schwarzbaum |first=Lisa |title=Lost in Translation |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=September 10, 2003 |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,479937,00.html |accessdate=July 29, 2009}}</ref> and the ''New York Times'' said, "At 18, the actress gets away with playing a 25-year-old woman by using her husky voice to test the level of acidity in the air ... Ms. Johansson is not nearly as accomplished a performer as Mr. Murray, but Ms. Coppola gets around this by using Charlotte's simplicity and curiosity as keys to her character."<ref>{{cite news |last=Mitchell |first=Elvis |title=An American in Japan, Making a Connection |work=New York Times |url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9803E1D8133BF931A2575AC0A9659C8B63 |date=September 12, 2003 |accessdate=July 24, 2009}}</ref> Johansson won the [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role|BAFTA Award]]<ref name="bafta">{{cite web |title=Actress in a Leading Role 2003 |url=http://www.bafta.org/awards-database.html?year=2003&category=Film&award=Actress+in+a+Leading+Role |publisher=British Academy of Film and Television Arts |accessdate=July 29, 2009}}</ref> and the [[Boston Society of Film Critics Award for Best Actress]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thebsfc.org/PastWin.html#d2003 |title=BSFC Winners 2003 |publisher=Boston Society of Film Critics |accessdate=July 29, 2009}}</ref> and was nominated for the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress&nbsp;<U+2013> Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Golden Globe Award for Best Actress]].<ref name="gglobes">{{cite web |title=Scarlett Johansson |publisher=Hollywood Foreign Press Association |url=http://www.goldenglobes.org/browse/member/30173 |accessdate=July 29, 2009}}</ref> She received nominations from a number of film critic organizations, including the [[Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Supporting Actress|Broadcast Film Critics Association]],<ref>{{cite web |title=The 9th Critics' Choice Awards Winners and Nominations |url=http://www.bfca.org/ccawards/2003.php |publisher=Broadcast Film Critics Association |accessdate=July 29, 2009}}</ref> the [[Chicago Film Critics Association Award for Best Actress|Chicago Film Critics Association]],<ref name="nytawards">{{cite news |title=Scarlett Johansson |url=http://movies.nytimes.com/person/200222/Scarlett-Johansson/awards |work=New York Times |accessdate=July 29, 2009}}</ref> the [[Phoenix Film Critics Society Award for Best Actress|Phoenix Film Critics Society]]<ref name="phoenix">{{cite web |title=Phoenix Film Critics Society Archive of Past Winners |url=http://cinemaclips.com/PFCSarchive.htm |publisher=Phoenix Film Critics Society |accessdate=July 29, 2009}}</ref> and the [[Chlotrudis Award for Best Actress|Chlotrudis Awards]].<ref>{{cite web |title=2004, 10th Annual Awards |publisher=Chlotrudis Society for Independent Films |url=http://www.chlotrudis.org/awards/archives/tenth/index.html#actress |accessdate=July 29, 2009}}</ref>

Johansson played Griet in [[Peter Webber]]'s ''[[Girl with a Pearl Earring (film)|Girl with a Pearl Earring]]''. While noting, "Audiences feel as if they are spying on a moment of artistic inspiration when painter Vermeer creates the title work", ''[[USA Today]]'' praised her, suggesting, "[She] is having a banner year that Oscar voters should recognize."<ref>{{cite news |first=Claudia |last=Puig |title=This 'Pearl' is of great value |url=http://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/reviews/2003-12-11-pearl-earring_x.htm |date=December 11, 2003 |accessdate=July 29, 2009 | work=USA Today}}</ref> In his review for ''[[the New Yorker]]'', [[Anthony Lane]] said, "What keeps Webber<U+2019>s movie alive is the tenseness of the setup ... and, above all, the presence of Johansson. She is often wordless and close to plain onscreen, but wait for the ardor with which she can summon a closeup and bloom under its gaze; this is her film, not Vermeer<U+2019>s, all the way."<ref>{{cite journal |first=Anthony |last= Lane |title=Girl with a Pearl Earring |work=[[The New Yorker]] |url=http://www.newyorker.com/arts/reviews/film/girl_with_a_pearl_earring_webber |date=December 22, 2003 |accessdate=July 29, 2009}}</ref> [[Owen Gleiberman]], for ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', wrote of her "nearly silent performance", observing, "The interplay on her face of fear, ignorance, curiosity, and sex is intensely dramatic."<ref>{{cite journal |first=Owen |last=Gleiberman |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,535689,00.html|title=Girl With a Pearl Earring (2003) |date=December 3, 2003 |accessdate=July 29, 2009}}</ref> She was nominated for the Golden Globe for Best Actress in a Drama<ref name="gglobes" /> and the [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role]].<ref name="bafta" /> She was also nominated by the [[London Film Critics Circle Award for Best Actress|London Film Critics' Circle]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Crowe Leads Race for London Critics' Awards |publisher=Contact Music|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/new/xmlfeed.nsf/mndwebpages/crowe%20leads%20race%20for%20london%20critics.%20awards |date=January 5, 2004 |accessdate=July 30, 2009}}</ref> the [[Phoenix Film Critics Society Award for Best Actress|Phoenix Film Critics Society]]<ref name="phoenix" /> and the [[British Independent Film Awards]].<ref>{{cite web |title=2004 Nominations |url=http://www.bifa.org.uk/nominations/2004 |publisher=British Independent Film Awards |accessdate=July 30, 2009}}</ref>

Johansson was invited to join the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]], in June 2004.<ref name="Oscars">{{cite news |url=http://www.oscars.org/press/pressreleases/2004/04.06.28.html |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080111195816/http://www.oscars.org/press/pressreleases/2004/04.06.28.html |archivedate=January 11, 2008 |title=Academy Invites 127 to Membership |publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences |date=June 28, 2004}}</ref> In the same year, she voiced a role in ''[[The SpongeBob SquarePants Movie]]'' and appeared in an adaptation of [[Oscar Wilde]]'s ''[[Lady Windermere's Fan]]'' entitled ''[[A Good Woman (film)|A Good Woman]]'', opposite [[Helen Hunt]] and [[Tom Wilkinson]]. It received a limited U.S. release, and was both a box office<ref>{{cite web |title=A Good Woman |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=goodwoman.htm |accessdate=August 1, 2009}}</ref> and critical<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/good_woman/ |title=A Good Woman |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=August 1, 2009}}</ref> failure. It was described by the ''New York Times'' as a "misbegotten Hollywood-minded screen adaptation" with "an excruciating divide between the film's British actors (led by Tom Wilkinson and Stephen Campbell Moore), who are comfortable delivering Wilde's aphorisms ... and its American marquee names, Helen Hunt and Scarlett Johansson, [who have] little connection to the English language as spoken in the high Wildean style."<ref>{{cite news |url=http://movies.nytimes.com/2006/02/03/movies/03woma.html |title=A Good Woman (2004) |work=New York Times |date=February 3, 2006 |accessdate=August 1, 2009 | first=Stephen | last=Holden}}</ref> She also appeared in the critically-panned,<ref>{{cite web |title=The Perfect Score (2004) |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/perfect_score/ |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=July 30, 2009}}</ref> teen, heist film ''[[The Perfect Score]]'' and in ''[[In Good Company (2004 film)|In Good Company]]'', in a supporting role opposite [[Topher Grace]] and [[Dennis Quaid]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/in_good_company/ |title=In Good Company (2004) |accessdate = July 30, 2009 |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]}}</ref> Her performance in the dark, Southern drama, ''[[A Love Song for Bobby Long]]'', earned her a third Golden Globe for Best Actress nomination.<ref name="gglobes" /> Johansson was involved for a short time with the film ''[[Mission: Impossible III]]'', but was not officially cast because of scheduling conflicts, although a falling out with the film's star, [[Tom Cruise]], was reported.<ref name="msnbc">{{cite news |publisher=MSNBC |title=Scarlett Johansson escapes Cruise's clutches |url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/8133757/ |accessdate=July 18, 2006 |first=Jeannette |last=Walls |date=June 20, 2005}}</ref>

=== 2005<U+2013>07 ===
[[File:Scarlett Johansson.jpg|thumb|right|upright|alt=A young woman with tousled medium length blonde hair loosely around her shoulders and face, looking to her right, her right arm slightly behind her, stands in the middle of a group of men. She is dressed in denim jeans, a light gray short sleeved shirt and a camera hangs around her neck.|Johansson at the film set of ''[[Vicky Cristina Barcelona]]'' in 2007]]

In July 2005, Johansson starred, with [[Ewan McGregor]], in [[Michael Bay]]'s science fiction film, ''[[The Island (2005 film)|The Island]]'', in dual roles as Sarah Jordan and her clone, Jordan Two Delta. The film was a domestic financial failure<ref name="BOM$">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=1854&p=.htm|title='Island' Deserted, 'Chocolate Factory,' 'Wedding' Take Cake|last=Gray|first=Brandon|date=July 25, 2005|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=8 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Island (2005) |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=island05.htm |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=July 31, 2009}}</ref> and received mixed critical reviews.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Island (2005) |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/island/ |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=August 3, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Island |url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/island?q=The%20Island |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=August 3, 2009}}</ref> In contrast, her role as Nola, the American actress with whom Chris ([[Jonathan Rhys Meyers]]) is obsessed, in the [[Woody Allen]]-directed drama ''[[Match Point]]'', was well-received. The ''New York Times'' said, "Ms. Johansson and Mr. Rhys-Meyers manage some of the best acting seen in a Woody Allen movie in a long time, escaping the archness and emotional disconnection that his writing often imposes."<ref>{{cite news |url=http://movies.nytimes.com/2005/12/28/movies/28matc.html?_r=1 |title=Match Point (2005) |first=A. O. |last=Scott |work=New York Times |date=December 28, 2005 |accessdate=July 31, 2009}}</ref> [[Mick LaSalle]], writing in the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'', said, "[Johansson] is a powerhouse from the word go", and, "[Her performance] borders on astonishing."<ref>{{cite news |first=Mick |last=LaSalle |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2006/01/06/DDG4SGHCJP1.DTL |title=Advantage Allen. Woody has done well to leave New York for London. He's back in the game with 'Match Point.' |date=January 6, 2006 |accessdate=July 31, 2009 | work=The San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref> Johansson received her fourth Golden Globe nomination,<ref name="gglobes" /> and one from the [[Chicago Film Critics Association]], for [[Chicago Film Critics Association Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]].<ref name="nytawards" />

In another collaboration with Allen, Johansson was cast opposite [[Hugh Jackman]] and Allen in the 2006 feature, ''[[Scoop (2006 film)|Scoop]]''. While the film enjoyed a modest worldwide box office success,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=scoop.htm |title=Scoop |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=August 2, 2009}}</ref> it received mixed reviews by critics.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/scoop/ |title=Scoop (2006) |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=August 2, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/scoop |title=Scoop |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=August 2, 2009}}</ref> The ''New York Times'' called the film "not especially funny yet oddly appealing" and cited parallels to ''[[The Thin Man (film)|The Thin Man]]'', saying, "[while] Johansson is certainly no Myrna Loy, [her] performance is all over the place ... but finally works for a film that is itself all over the place. Mr. Allen seems happy to just watch her strut her stuff, and after a while so are we."<ref>{{cite news |first=Manohla |last=Dargis |url=http://movies.nytimes.com/2006/07/28/movies/28scoo.html |title=<U+2018>Scoop<U+2019>: Shades of Nick and Nora, With Woody Allen<U+2019>s Shtick |work=New York Times |date=July 28, 2006 |accessdate=August 2, 2009}}</ref> ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine said, "Johansson doesn<U+2019>t have the natural buoyancy to play a screwball Nancy Drew, [but] she<U+2019>s smart enough to know what<U+2019>s needed (a young Diane Keaton), and manages to rouse herself",<ref>{{cite web |title=Sea, Sun, and Hungry Sex |url=http://nymag.com/movies/reviews/18468/index1.html |work=[[New York Magazine]] |accessdate=August 2, 2009}}</ref> while ''[[USA Today]]'' criticized "her delivery of Allenesque one-liners" as "clunky", and "sometimes, she seems in over her head playing opposite Allen."<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/reviews/2006-07-27-scoop_x.htm |title=Here's the 'Scoop': Allen amuses |work=[[USA Today]] |date=July 27, 2006 |accessdate=August 2, 2009 | first=Claudia | last=Puig}}</ref> The same year, she appeared in [[Brian De Palma]]'s ''[[The Black Dahlia (film)|The Black Dahlia]]'', a [[film noir]] shot in Los Angeles and [[Bulgaria]]. Johansson later said she was a De Palma fan and had wanted to work with him on the film, even though she thought that she was "physically wrong" for the part.<ref name="moviesonline">{{cite web |first=Sheila |last=Roberts |publisher=MoviesOnline |title=Black Dahlia Interview: Scarlett Johansson |url=http://www.moviesonline.ca/movienews_9906.html |accessdate=September 13, 2006}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> Her reviews were mixed. [[CNN.com]] noted, "[Johansson] takes to the pulpy period atmosphere as if it were oxygen,"<ref name="cnn.comreview">{{cite news |first=Owen |last=Gleiberman |title='Black Dahlia' a stylish misfire |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2006/SHOWBIZ/Movies/09/15/ew.mov.blackdahlia/ |publisher=CNN |accessdate=August 3, 2009 |date=September 15, 2006}}</ref> whereas the ''[[Kalamazoo Gazette]]'' referred to Johansson as "miscast".<ref name="KalamazooGazette">{{cite news |title=Stylish ''Black Dahlia'' recalls crime dramas of the 1940s |work=[[Kalamazoo Gazette]] |accessdate=August 3, 2009 |url=http://www.mlive.com/movies/kzgazette/index.ssf?/base/features-0/1158333613125640.xml&coll=7}}</ref>

Johansson next had a supporting role in the [[Christopher Nolan]] thriller ''[[The Prestige (film)|The Prestige]]'' (2006), again opposite Hugh Jackman, as well as [[Christian Bale]]. Nolan, who described Johansson as possessing an "ambiguity... a shielded quality",<ref>{{cite web |title=Scarlett Johansson Is the Sexiest Woman Alive, 2006 |work=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |url=http://www.esquire.com/women/the-sexiest-woman-alive/scarlett-johansson-pics |date=October 31, 2006 |accessdate=August 3, 2009}}</ref> said he was "very keen" for her to play the role.<ref name="casting">{{cite news|first=Chris |last=Carle |title=Casting The Prestige |publisher=IGN |date=October 12, 2006 |url=http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/738/738782p1.html |accessdate=August 3, 2009}}</ref> Johansson said, "[she] loved working with [Nolan]", and he was "incredibly focused and driven and involved, and really involved in the performance in every aspect."<ref>{{cite web |first=Paul |last=Fischer |title=Interview: Scarlett Johansson for ''Scoop'' |url=http://www.darkhorizons.com/interviews/1039/scarlett-johansson-for-scoop- |accessdate=August 3, 2009 |date=July 26, 2006 |publisher=[[Dark Horizons]]}}</ref> The film was both a critical<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/prestige |title=The Prestige (2006) |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=August 3, 2009}}</ref> and a worldwide box office<ref>{{cite web |title=The Prestige |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=prestige.htm |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=August 3, 2009}}</ref> success, recommended by the ''Los Angeles Times'' as "an adult, provocative piece of work."<ref>{{cite web |first=Kenneth |last=Turan |title=The Prestige |url=http://www.calendarlive.com/printedition/calendar/cl-et-prestige20oct20,0,1454799.story |date=October 20, 2006 |accessdate=August 3, 2009}}</ref> Also in 2006, Johansson starred in a short film directed by [[Bennett Miller]] and set to [[Bob Dylan]]'s "When the Deal Goes Down...", released to promote Dylan's album, ''[[Modern Times (Bob Dylan album)|Modern Times]]''.<ref name="guitar">{{cite web |title=Bob Dylan Short Film Details |publisher=UltimateGuitar.com |accessdate=September 15, 2006 |url=http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/press_releases/bob_dylan_short_film_details.html?200609150816}}</ref>

Johansson starred in 2007's ''[[The Nanny Diaries (film)|The Nanny Diaries]]'', alongside [[Laura Linney]]. The film performed only marginally well at the box office,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=main&id=nannydiaries.htm |title=The Nanny Diaries |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=August 5, 2009}}</ref> and was critically-panned.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/nanny_diaries/ |title=The Nanny Diaries (2007) |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=August 5, 2009}}</ref> Johansson's reviews were mixed, with ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' saying, "[She] essays an engaging heroine",<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117934447.html?categoryid=31&cs=1 |title=The Nanny Diaries |first=Lael |last=Loewenstein |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=August 17, 2007 |accessdate=August 5, 2009}}</ref> while ''The New Yorker'' criticized her for looking "merely confused" while "trying to give the material a plausible emotional center".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newyorker.com/arts/critics/cinema/2007/09/03/070903crci_cinema_denby |title=Eastern, Western |first=David |last=Denby |work=[[The New Yorker]] |date=September 3, 2007 |accessdate=August 5, 2009}}</ref> In his review for the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'', Mick LaSalle said, "There's something painful about watching Scarlett Johansson, who looks as if she never had an indecisive moment in her life, struggle to seem ineffectual."<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=/c/a/2007/08/24/DDJJRND9A.DTL&type=movies |title=Review: 'The Nanny Diaries': Now the devil needs child care |first=Mick |last=LaSalle |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |date=August 24, 2007 |accessdate=August 5, 2009}}</ref>

=== 2008<U+2013>present ===
In 2008, she starred in ''[[The Other Boleyn Girl (2008 film)|The Other Boleyn Girl]]'', opposite [[Natalie Portman]] and [[Eric Bana]],<ref name="mweb">{{cite news |publisher=MovieWeb |title=Scarlett Johansson Is The Other Boleyn Girl |url=http://www.movieweb.com/news/NEc3MlhhG6Qzfg |accessdate=July 18, 2006 |date=July 17, 2006}}</ref> a film which garnered mixed reviews.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Other Boleyn Girl |url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/otherboleyngirl |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=August 7, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://uk.rottentomatoes.com/m/other_boleyn_girl/ |title=The Other Boleyn Girl (2008) |accessdate=August 7, 2009}}</ref> Writing for ''Rolling Stone'', Pete Travers criticized the film for "[moving] in frustrating herks and jerks", but was more positive in his assessment of Johansson and Portman, and wrote, "What works is the combustible teaming of Natalie Portman and Scarlett Johansson, who give the Boleyn hotties a tough core of intelligence and wit, swinging the film's sixteenth-century protofeminist issues handily into this one."<ref>{{cite web |last=Travers |first=Peter |url=http://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/movie/14584631/review/18947849/other_boleyn_girl |title=Other Boleyn Girl |work=Rolling Stone |date=March 20, 2008 |accessdate=August 7, 2009}}</ref> ''Variety'' credited the cast as "almost flawless ... at the top of its game", citing "Johansson<U+2019>s quieter Mary ... as the pic<U+2019>s emotional center, her tender love story with the conflicted monarch evoking the only genuine feelings on display."<ref>{{cite news |title=The Other Boleyn Girl |first=Derek |last=Elley |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' |date=February 18, 2009 |url=http://www.variety.com/index.asp?layout=festivals&jump=review&id=2478&reviewid=VE1117936222&cs=1 |accessdate=August 7, 2009}}</ref>

She filmed her third Woody Allen film, ''[[Vicky Cristina Barcelona]]'', in Spain,<ref name="usatoday807" /> appearing opposite [[Javier Bardem]] and [[Pen<U+00E9>lope Cruz]]. The film was one of Allen's most profitable<ref>{{cite web |title=Vicky Cristina Barcelona |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=vickycristinabarcelona.htm |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=August 7, 2009}}</ref> and appeared on many critics' top ten lists of the best films of 2008.<ref name=mctop08>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/awards/2008/toptens.shtml |title=Metacritic: 2008 Film Critic Top Ten Lists |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=January 11, 2009}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> Overall, the film received generally favorable reviews<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/vickycristinabarcelona |title=Vicky Cristina Barcelona |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=August 7, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Vick Cristina Barcelona |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/vicky_cristina_barcelona/ |accessdate=July 6, 2009|work=Rotten Tomatoes}}</ref> and brought co-star Cruz numerous awards, including the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Pen<U+00E9>lope Cruz Awards |url=http://www.variety.com/profiles/people/Awards/29249/Pen%C3%A9lope+Cruz.html |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=August 7, 2009}} {{Dead link|date=August 2010|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref> Johansson was described as being "open and malleable" and "serves as a nice contrast to the [other actors]".<ref>{{cite news |first=Todd |last=McCarthy |title=Vicky Cristina Barcelona |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=May 19, 2008 |accessdate=August 7, 2009 |url=http://www.variety.com/index.asp?layout=festivals&jump=review&reviewid=VE1117937165&cs=1}}</ref>

Johansson played Silken Floss, a [[femme fatale]] and ally of [[Samuel L. Jackson]]'s villain [[The Octopus]], in [[Frank Miller (comics)|Frank Miller]]'s film noir, comedy adaptation of ''[[The Spirit (film)|The Spirit]]''. The film, described as "a great-looking movie with an awkward balance of pulp noir and campy self-awareness"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.seattlepi.com/movies/393420_spirit25q.html |title='The Spirit' looks great, but it sure doesn't move us |first=Sean |last=Axmaker |work=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |date=December 28, 2008 |accessdate=August 8, 2009}}</ref> and "style without substance, style whirling in a senseless void",<ref>{{cite web |first=Roger |last=Ebert |url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20081223/REVIEWS/812239987 |title=The Spirit |work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=December 23, 2008 |accessdate=August 8, 2009}}</ref> received mostly poor reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_spirit/ |title=The Spirit (2008) |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=August 8, 2009}}</ref>

Johansson appeared in the role of Anna, a yoga instructor, in the 2009 ensemble cast of ''[[He's Just Not That into You (film)|He's Just Not That Into You]]'', with [[Jennifer Connelly]], [[Bradley Cooper]], [[Drew Barrymore]] and [[Kevin Connolly (actor)|Kevin Connolly]]. The film was a box office success<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=hesjustnotthatintoyou.htm |title=He's Just Not That into You |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=August 8, 2009}}</ref> but only gained average critical reception.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/hesjustnot |title=He's Just Not That Into You |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=August 8, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=He's Just Not That Into You (2009) |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/hes_just_not_that_into_you/ |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=August 8, 2009}}</ref> The ''San Francisco Chronicle'' review notes, "[The film] never soars, but it never flags" yet lauds Johansson, saying, "She has become a deft comic actress."<ref>{{cite news |first=Mick |last=LaSalle |title=He's Just Not That Into You |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2009/02/05/DDHM15N9QF.DTL&type=movies |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |date=February 6, 2009 |accessdate=August 8, 2009}}</ref> The ''Los Angeles Times'' calls the film an "anti-romantic romantic comedy" and cites the scenario in which Johansson appears with Jennifer Connelly and Bradley Cooper as having "more meat than others", making it "one of the best."<ref>{{cite news |first=Betsy |last=Sharkey |title='He's Just Not That Into You' is breezy anti-romantic comedy |work=Los Angeles Times |date=February 6, 2009 |accessdate=August 8, 2009 |url=http://www.calendarlive.com/movies/cl-et-intoyou6-2009feb06,0,813856.story}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> The ''[[Baltimore Sun]]'' criticized the film, saying, "[It] stumbles somewhat when it tries to get serious", but praised Johansson for "proving she doesn't need Woody Allen to be funny."<ref>{{cite news |first=Chris |Kaltenbach |title='Just Not That Into You' is just not believable |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/bal-to.notjust06feb06,0,7826626.story |work=[[Baltimore Sun]] |date=February 6, 2009 |accessdate=August 8, 2009}}</ref>

In March 2009, Johansson signed on to play [[Black Widow (Natalia Romanova)|Natasha Romanoff]] in ''[[Iron Man 2]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news-briefs.ew.com/2009/03/12/scarlett-johans/ |title='Iron Man 2': Scarlett Johansson cast as Black Widow |first=Jeremy |last=Medina |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=March 12, 2009|accessdate=August 8, 2009}}</ref> after a scheduling conflict forced [[Emily Blunt]] to drop out of the part.<ref>{{cite news |first=Nicole |last=Sperling |title='Iron Man 2': Scarlett Johansson to replace Emily Blunt as Black Widow? |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=February 13, 2009 |url=http://hollywoodinsider.ew.com/2009/02/iron-man-2-will.html |accessdate=August 8, 2009}}</ref> The film, released in May 2010, was directed by [[Jon Favreau]] and also starred [[Robert Downey, Jr.]], [[Gwyneth Paltrow]], [[Don Cheadle]], [[Mickey Rourke]], [[Samuel L. Jackson]] and [[Sam Rockwell]].<ref name="comic">{{cite web |first=Nicole |last=Sperling |title='Iron Man 2' crew returns to Comic-Con as conquering heroes and sets off a whole new buzz bomb |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=July 26, 2009 |url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2009/07/26/iron-man-2-comiccon/ |accessdate=August 8, 2009}}</ref> Appearing at [[Comic-Con]] in [[San Diego, California]] on July 26, 2009, Johansson joked about her audition for the film, saying it consisted of "a couple of deep knee bends and lunges", but Favreau credited her with performing her own stunts: "All the fighting and wire work is her own. She worked really hard and it shows on the screen."<ref name="comic" />

=== Theatre ===
Johansson made her first stage appearance in the [[Off Broadway]] play ''Sophistry''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/16/theater/theaterspecial/16scarlett.htm|title=Definitely Didn<U+2019>t Get Lost in Translation|last=Isherwood|first=Charles|date=May 12, 2010|work=The New York Times|accessdate=November 14, 2010}}</ref> In 2009, Johansson made her debut on Broadway, as Catherine Carbone in the drama ''[[A View from the Bridge]]'', written by [[Arthur Miller]] and directed by [[Gregory Mosher]]. [[Liev Schreiber]] played opposite her.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.broadway.com/buzz/scarlett-johansson-makes-her-broadway-debut-opposite-tony-winner-liev-schreiber-view-bridge/ |publisher=Broadway.com |title=Scarlett Johansson to Make Her Broadway Debut Opposite Liev Schreiber in A View From the Bridge |date=October 26, 2009 |accessdate=February 3, 2010}}</ref> Johansson was nominated for and won the 2010 [[Tony Award for Best Performance by a Featured Actress in a Play]] for her role in the play.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/14/theater/theaterspecial/14tony.html?hp|publisher=The New York Times |title=The 64th Annual Tony Awards |date=June 14, 2010 | first=Patrick | last=Healy}}</ref>

== Endorsements ==
Johansson has appeared in advertising campaigns for [[Calvin Klein]], [[L'Or<U+00E9>al]], [[Louis Vuitton]]<ref name="D&G" /> and has been the face of Spanish brand [[Mango (clothing)|Mango]] since 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sassybella.com/2009/05/news-bite-scarlett-mango-henry-holland-alex-wang-qa-angels-pregnant/ |title=News Bite: Scarlett for Mango, Henry Holland & Alex Wang Q&A, and are all the VS Angels pregnant? |publisher=Sassybella.com |date= |accessdate=2010-07-20}}</ref> After appearing at the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]'s Costume Institute Gala with [[Domenico Dolce]] and [[Stefano Gabbana]], Johansson was announced as the face of the new [[Dolce & Gabbana]] make-up collection in early 2009.<ref name="D&G">{{cite news |title=Scarlett likes it hot: Johansson goes for the Marilyn Monroe look in striking D&G ad |work=[[Daily Mail]] |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-1121883/Scarlett-likes-hot-Johansson-goes-Marilyn-Monroe-look-striking-D-G-ad.html |date=January 19, 2009 |accessdate=August 9, 2009}}</ref> She made a personal appearance at the London store, [[Selfridges]], on July 31, 2009, to help launch and promote the line.<ref name="dolce">{{cite web |title=Scarlett Johansson Launches Dolce & Gabbana The Makeup in London |publisher=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=July 29, 2009 |accessdate=August 1, 2009 |url=http://stylenews.peoplestylewatch.com/2009/07/31/scarlett-johansson-launches-dolce-gabbana-the-makeup-in-london/}}</ref>

== Music career ==
In 2005, Johansson was considered for the role of Maria<ref name="Maria">{{cite news |first=James |last=Inverne |title=Lloyd Webber Wants Scarlett Johansson for London Sound of Music |url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/92834-Lloyd_Webber_Wants_Scarlett_Johansson_for_London_Sound_of_Music |accessdate=August 23, 2007 |date=May 9, 2005 |work=Playbill News}}</ref> in [[Andrew Lloyd Webber|Andrew Lloyd Webber's]] [[West End theatre|West End]] revival of ''[[The Sound of Music]]'', though the role ultimately went to newcomer [[Connie Fisher]] after she won [[BBC|BBC's]] talent show ''[[How Do You Solve a Problem Like Maria|How Do You Solve a Problem Like Maria?]]''<ref name="ConnieFisher">{{cite news |title=I would never mime on stage |date=August 17, 2007 |first=Karen |last=Price |url=http://icwales.icnetwork.co.uk/0900entertainment/0050artsnews/tm_headline=i-would-never-mime-on-stage&method=full&objectid=19648489&siteid=50082-name_page.html |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20071116104907/http://icwales.icnetwork.co.uk/0900entertainment/0050artsnews/tm_headline=i-would-never-mime-on-stage&method=full&objectid=19648489&siteid=50082-name_page.html |archivedate=November 16, 2007 |accessdate=August 23, 2007}}</ref> Released on May 8, 2006, Johansson sang the track "[[Summertime (song)|Summertime]]" for ''[[Unexpected Dreams|Unexpected Dreams&nbsp;<U+2013> Songs From the Stars]]'', a [[non-profit]] collection of songs recorded by Hollywood actors. She performed with [[The Jesus and Mary Chain]] for a special [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival|Coachella]] Reunion Show in [[Indio, California]] in April 2007.<ref name="coachella">{{cite news |first=Jeff |last=Leeds |work=New York Times |title=Coachella: Scarlett Johansson Joins Jesus and Mary Chain |url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2007/04/28/coachella-scarlett-johansson-joins-jesus-and-mary-chain/|author=Jeff Leeds|date=April 28, 2007|accessdate=April 28, 2007}}</ref>

[[File:ScarlettJohanssonFeb07.jpg|thumb|left|upright|alt=A close up of a smiling young woman, her blonde hair pulled back, wearing a silver tiara, silver earrings and a black cowl-necked coat. She is standing outside in bright sunlight.|Johansson at the [[Hasty Pudding Theatricals|Hasty Pudding]] Woman of the Year Parade in Cambridge, MA in February 2007]]

In 2007, she appeared as the leading lady in [[Justin Timberlake|Justin Timberlake's]] music video, for "[[What Goes Around.../...Comes Around]]", which was nominated in August 2007 for video of the year at the [[MTV Video Music Awards]].<ref name="MTV video">{{cite news |date=August 8, 2007 |title=Justin Timberlake, Beyonce lead MTV Video Music Awards with 7 nods each |accessdate=August 23, 2007 |url=http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/ae/s_521050.html}}</ref>

In mid-2007, Johansson spent about a month in [[Maurice, Louisiana]] recording an album at Dockside Studio, a rural {{convert|12|acre|m2|sing=on}} complex.<ref name="advertiser">{{cite web |work=Daily Advertiser |title=Scarlett Johansson Record Deal in the Works |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,221001,00.html |date=October 16, 2006}}</ref> The album, consisting of one original song and ten cover versions of [[Tom Waits]] songs,<ref name="localfav">{{cite news |last=Ryzik |first=Melena |title=Local favourite |work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]] |url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/film/local-favourite/2007/09/16/1189881329353.html |date=September 17, 2007 |accessdate=September 16, 2007}}</ref><ref name="foxnews">{{cite news |title=Scarlett Johansson Record Deal in the Works |first=Roger |last=Friedman |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,221001,00.html |publisher=Fox News |accessdate=October 16, 2006 |date=October 16, 2006}}</ref> was produced by [[Dave Sitek]] of [[TV on the Radio]] and features [[David Bowie]],<ref name="observer">{{cite news |first=Barney |last=Hoskyns |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2008/may/18/popandrock.shopping18 |title=Scarlett Johansson, Anywhere I Lay My Head |work=The Observer |date=May 18, 2008 |accessdate=October 11, 2008 | location=London}}</ref> members from the [[Yeah Yeah Yeahs]]<ref name="debut">{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/news/globe/living/articles/2007/08/04/a_johansson_debut/ |title=A Johansson debut |date=August 4, 2007 |work=Boston Globe |accessdate=August 23, 2007}}</ref> and [[Celebration (band)|Celebration]].<ref name="Celebration">{{cite news |title=Movie Minute: Hot Rod |url=http://www.mtv.ca/news/article.jhtml?id=2598| publisher=MTV |date=August 3, 2007 |accessdate=August 23, 2007}}</ref><ref name="Oct07">{{cite news |first=Julie |title=Scarlett Johansson: From Actress to Singer |url=http://www.clevelandleader.com/node/2612 |work=[[Cleveland Leader]] |date=August 29, 2007 |accessdate=August 29, 2007}}</ref> Released on May 20, 2008, it was entitled ''[[Anywhere I Lay My Head]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Kharas |first=Kev |title=David Bowie to guest on Scarlett Johansson's Tom Waits covers record |publisher=[[Drowned in Sound]] |date=February 14, 2008 |url=http://drownedinsound.com/news/2930510}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Scarlett Johansson to Release Album in May|url=http://www.andpop.com/2008/01/09/scarlett-johansson-to-release-album-in-may/ |accessdate = April 22, 2008 |first=Max |last=Whiteside |date=January 9, 2008 |publisher=andPOP}}</ref> Reviews of the album were mixed, or average.<ref>{{cite web |title=Anywhere I Lay My Head by Scarlett Johansson|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/artists/johanssonscarlett/anywhereilaymyhead |publisher=Metacritic}}</ref> ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' commented, "There's nothing particularly compelling about Scarlett Johansson's singing."<ref name="SMW">{{cite web|url=http://www.spin.com/reviews/scarlett-johansson-anywhere-i-lay-my-head-atco|title=Scarlett Johansson, 'Anywhere I Lay My Head' (ATCO) Bombshell actress coos coyly behind hipster sound sculptor. |last=Wood|first=Mikael|date=May 29, 2008|publisher=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|accessdate=8 May 2010}}</ref> Conversely, some critics found it to be "surprisingly alluring",<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2008/may/16/popandrock2 |first=Dorian |last=Lynskey |work=The Guardian |title=Scarlett Johansson, Anywhere I Lay My Head |date=May 16, 2008 | location=London}}</ref> "a bravely eccentric selection",<ref name="observer" /> and "a brilliant album" with "ghostly magic".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/scarlett-johansson/9660 nme.com |first=Priya |last=Elan |title=Scarlett Johansson&nbsp;<U+2014> Anywhere I Lay My Head |publisher=NME |date=May 2, 2008 |accessdate=July 24, 2009}}</ref> The album was named the "23rd best album of 2008" by ''[[NME]]''<ref>{{cite journal |title=NME's Top 50 Albums Of 2008&nbsp;<U+2013> Year-End List |work=NME Magazine |date=December 10, 2008 |author=NME editors}}</ref> and peaked at #1 on the ''Billboard'' [[Top Heatseekers]] chart and #126 on the [[Billboard 200]] chart.<ref>{{cite web |title= Anywhere I Lay My Head (2008) |url=http://www.billboard.com/#/album/scarlett-johansson/anywhere-i-lay-my-head/1136979 |work=Billboard |accessdate=August 8, 2009}}</ref> Of her album, Johansson said, "I had this golden opportunity to record and thought I would do maybe an album of standards, because I<U+2019>m not a songwriter. I<U+2019>m a vocalist."<ref>{{cite web |first=Joshua |laast=Ostroff |url=http://www.exclaim.ca/articles/multiarticlesub.aspx?csid1=122&csid2=778&fid1=31350 |title=Scarlett Johansson Down in the Bayou |work=Exclaim! |date = June 2008|accessdate=July 24, 2009}}</ref> Johansson said for her recording she "wanted to have space and [she] wanted to be in a remote place where all of us could just be ourselves and not worry about anyone trying to listen in or get in on that."<ref>{{cite web |first=Amanda |last=Petrusich |title=Scarlett Johansson |url=http://pitchfork.com/features/interviews/6848-scarlett-johansson/ |publisher=Pitchfork |date=May 12, 2008 |accessdate=July 24, 2009}}</ref> Johansson said in an interview that she started listening to Tom Waits when she was 11 or 12.<ref>{{cite web |first=Stephen |last=|Mooallem |title=Scarlett Johansson |url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/music/scarlett-johansson/2/ |work=[[Interview Magazine]] |date=November 30, 2008 |accessdate=July 24, 2009}}</ref> Of Tom Waits, Johansson said in an interview, "His melodies are so beautiful, his voice is so distinct and I had my own way of doing Tom Waits songs."<ref>{{cite web |first=Josh |last=Jackson |title=Scarlett Johansson and David Sitek talk Tom Waits Album |work=Paste Magazine |date=February 13, 2008 |accessdate=July 24, 2009 |url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2008/02/scarlett-johansson-and-david-sitek-talk-tom-waits.html}}</ref> In December 2008, MTV reported Johansson planned to follow-up ''Anywhere I Lay My Head'' with an album of all original music, saying, <U+201C>I don<U+2019>t think I<U+2019>d do covers, so it<U+2019>d be a project that I have to dedicate myself to. I feel like that<U+2019>s something for the future.<U+201D><ref>{{cite web |title=Scarlett Johansson Says She'll Record Another Album, Still Has Leonard Cohen On The Brain |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1601310/20081215/johansson__scarlett.jhtml |publisher=MTV |date=December 15, 2008 |accessdate=May 3, 2010}}</ref>

In 2009, Johansson covered [[Jeff Buckley]]'s "[[Last Goodbye (Jeff Buckley song)|Last Goodbye]]" for the soundtrack of ''[[He's Just Not That into You (film)|He's Just Not That Into You]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Scarlett Johansson Covers Jeff Buckley |publisher=Stereogum |date=January 27, 2009 |accessdate=July 24, 2009 |url=http://stereogum.com/archives/scarlett-johansson-covers-jeff-buckley_048421.html}}</ref> Released on September 8, 2009, she and singer/songwriter [[Pete Yorn]] recorded a collaborative album, ''[[Break Up (Scarlett Johansson and Pete Yorn album)|Break Up]]'', inspired by [[Serge Gainsbourg]]'s duets with [[Brigitte Bardot]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Edna |last=Gundersen |title=Listen as Yorn, Johansson 'Break Up' |url=http://www.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2009-05-21-break-up-album_N.htm |work=[[USA Today]] |date=May 12, 2009 |accessdate=July 24, 2009}}</ref>

In 2010, [[Steel Train]] released Terrible Thrills Vol. 1, which includes their favourite female artists singing songs from their [[Steel Train (album)|self-titled album]]. Johansson is the first artist on the album, singing "Bullet".{{Citation needed|date=November 2010}}

==Regarded as sex symbol==
Johansson is considered a "peerless [[sex symbol]]" by [[Channel 4]],<ref name="CH4SS">{{cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/programmes/the-100-greatest-sex-symbols/articles/the-results|title=The 100 Greatest Sex Symbols|date=February 13, 2009|publisher=[[Channel 4]]|accessdate=8 May 2010}}</ref> and she regularly appears at the top of lists of the sexiest women in the world. Johansson appeared on the cover of the March 2006 issue of ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' in the nude alongside actress [[Keira Knightley]] and fashion designer [[Tom Ford]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Table of Contents, March 2006 |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |url=http://www.vanityfair.com/magazine/toc/contents-200603 |accessdate=November 28, 2010}}</ref> ''[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]]'' named Johansson #6 in their Hot 100 Issue in 2006;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.maxim.com/girls/hot-100/77965/2006-hot-100.html?p=95 |title=2006 Hot 100 Photos |work=[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]] |accessdate=July 24, 2009}}</ref> #3 in 2007<ref>{{cite web |title=2007 Top 100 Photos |url=http://www.maxim.com/girls/hot-100/76385/2007-hot-100.html?p=98 |publisher=Maxim |accessdate=July 24, 2009}} {{Dead link|date=November 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> and #2 in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |title=2008 Hot 100 Photos |url=http://www.maxim.com/girls/hot-100/44007/2008-hot-100.html?p=99 |publisher=Maxim |accessdate=July 24, 2009}} {{Dead link|date=November 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> In November 2006, Johansson was named "Sexiest Woman Alive" by ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Esquire: Scarlett Johansson 'Sexiest' |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/09/29/AR2006092900856.html |date=September 29, 2006|accessdate=September 29, 2006|publisher=Washington Post}}</ref> In February 2007, she was named the "Sexiest Celebrity" of the year by ''[[Playboy]]''.<ref name="BTPB07">{{cite news|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/film-tv/news/iron-man-2-scarlett-johansson-fever-strikes-again-14782051.html|title=Iron Man 2: Scarlett Johansson fever strikes again.|date=April 27, 2010|publisher=[[The Belfast Telegraph]]|accessdate=8 May 2010}}</ref> During the filming of ''[[Match Point (film)|Match Point]]'', director Woody Allen described Johansson as "sexually overwhelming", saying that he found it "very hard to be extra witty around a sexually overwhelming, beautiful young woman who is wittier than you are."<ref>{{cite news |title=Allen Overwhelmed by Johansson's Sexuality |publisher=Hollywood.com |accessdate=May 17, 2009 |date=June 27, 2006 |url=http://www.hollywood.com/news/Allen_Overwhelmed_by_Johanssons_Sexuality/3521442}}</ref> In 2010, GQ Magazine named Johansson its Babe of The Year.<ref>{{cite web |title=GQ<U+2019>s Babe Of The Year Is Scarlett Johansson |url=http://iknowjack.radio.com/2010/11/16/gqs-babe-of-the-year-is-scarlett-johansson/}}</ref>

== Personal life ==
Johansson rarely discusses her personal life with the press, saying, "It's nice to have everybody not know your business."<ref>{{cite news |first=Pippa |last=Smith |title=Scarlett: The truth about my threesome |date=August 16, 2008 |accessdate=July 25, 2009 |work=The Independent (Ireland) |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/film-cinema/scarlett-the-truth--about-my-threesome-1456865.html}}</ref> 

She has been linked to many famous men, including [[Benicio del Toro]],<ref>{{cite news |title= Scarlett Johansson: the reluctant sex symbol |url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article5369980.ece |accessdate=January 2, 2009|first=Martyn |last=Palmer|date=December 27, 2008|work=The Times | location=London}}</ref> [[Jared Leto]],<ref name=USAKeck/> [[Justin Timberlake]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Actress Scarlett Johansson Refuses to Discuss Reported Fling With Singer Justin Timberlake |date=April 5, 2007 |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,264383,00.html |accessdate=January 2, 2009 |publisher=Fox News}}</ref> and her ''Black Dahlia'' co-star [[Josh Hartnett]], though Johansson denies she had a relationship with del Toro.<ref name=USAKeck>{{cite news |title=New year bright for Johansson |url=http://www.usatoday.com/life/people/2004-12-28-johansson-main_x.htm |accessdate=January 2, 2009 |first=William |last=Keck |date=December 28, 2004 |work=USA Today}}</ref> Johansson and Hartnett dated for about two years until the end of 2006, with Hartnett citing their busy lives as the reason for the split.<ref name=hartnettsplit>{{cite news |title=Hartnett Opens Up About 'Painful' Johansson Split|url=http://www.hollywood.com/news/Hartnett_Opens_Up_About_Painful_Johansson_Split/3651200 |publisher=Hollywood.com|date=January 31, 2007 |accessdate=July 24, 2009}}</ref>

[[File:Nobel Peace Prize Concert 2008 Scarlett Johansson Michael Caine.jpg|alt=A older man with gray hair, wearing glasses and dressed in a black suit and matching lavender shirt and tie stands on a stage in front of a dark curtain. A young woman with blonde hair pulled away from her face, wearing a sleeveless purple designer dress and high heels stands next to him, her right hand holding his left arm. Both are holding cordless microphones. There is blue backlighting that reflects off of the floor.|thumb|right|upright|Scarlett Johansson with [[Michael Caine]] at the Nobel Peace Prize Concert 2008]]

In a 2006 interview, Johansson expressed a concern about the potential conflict between the nature of human beings and the concept of [[monogamy]].<ref name="JWMSNBC">{{cite web|url=http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/10696087/|title=Johansson doesn<U+2019>t believe in monogamy|last=Walls|first=Jeannette|date=January 10, 2006|publisher=[[Msnbc.com]]|accessdate=8 May 2010}}</ref> However, she has stated "contrary to popular belief&nbsp;... [I am] not [[promiscuous]]" and that she works "really hard" when she's in a relationship "to make it work in a monogamous way."<ref>{{cite news |first=Sarah |last=Womack |coauthors=John Hiscock |title=Everyone should have HIV test twice a year, says Johansson |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1531149/Everyone-should-have-HIV-test-twice-a-year%2C-says-Johansson.html |work=Daily Telegraph |date=October 11, 2006| accessdate=December 5, 2006 | location=London}}</ref> She gets tested for [[HIV]] twice a year and has said, "It's part of being a decent human [and it is] just disgusting behavior when people don't. It's so irresponsible."<ref name=hivtest>{{cite news |title=Scarlett Johansson: 'I'm Not Promiscous' |date=October 9, 2006 |work=Washington Post |accessdate=July 24, 2009 |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/10/09/AR2006100900872.html}}</ref>

She started dating [[Canadians|Canadian]] actor [[Ryan Reynolds]] in 2007,<ref name="rreynold">{{cite news |last=Messer |first=Lesley |title=Scarlett Johansson & Ryan Reynolds Step Out in NYC |work=People |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20034177,00.html |date=April 7, 2007 |accessdate=September 19, 2007}}</ref> and on May 5, 2008, it was reported that the two were engaged.<ref>{{cite news |first=Alexis |last=Chiu |title=Scarlett Johansson & Ryan Reynolds Engaged! |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20197908,00.html |work=People |date=May 5, 2008 |accessdate=October 11, 2008}}</ref> On September 27, 2008, Johansson and Reynolds were married at a quiet ceremony near [[Tofino]], [[British Columbia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20238093,00.html |title=Just Married!&nbsp;<U+2014> Secret Weddings, Ryan Reynolds, Scarlett Johansson |last=Hamm |first=Liza |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=October 13, 2008 |quote=The weekend-long bash took place at the rugged-yet-luxurious Clayoquot Wilderness Resort, a remote outpost near the Canadian seaside village of Tofino, B.C. Located on Vancouver Island |accessdate=May 17, 2010}}</ref> They purchased a [[United States dollar|$]]2.8 million home together near [[Los Angeles]], [[California]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.usmagazine.com/healthylifestyle/news/scarlett-johansson-ryan-reynolds-buy-28-million-home-2010128|title=Scarlett Johansson, Ryan Reynolds Buy $2.8 Million Home|publisher=UsMagazine.com}}</ref> On December 14, 2010, Reynolds and Johansson announced that they had separated, saying "after long and careful consideration on both our parts, we've decided to end our marriage...We entered our relationship with love and it's with love and kindness we leave it."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20449544,00.html |title=Scarlett Johansson & Ryan Reynolds Split Up|publisher=people.com |accessdate=2010-12-14}}</ref> Reynolds filed for divorce on December 23, 2010 in Los Angeles, citing irreconcilable differences. Johansson filed her divorce response simultaneously.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tmz.com/2010/12/14/ryan-reynolds-scarlett-johansson-file-for-divorce-separation-documents-prenup-community-property/ |title=Ryan Reynolds Files For Divorce From Scarlett|publisher=TMZ |accessdate=2010-12-23}}</ref>

She has criticized the media and Hollywood for promoting an image that causes unhealthy diets and [[eating disorder]]s among women, saying, "Being ultra-thin is not sexy at all. Women shouldn't be forced to conform to unrealistic and unhealthy body images that the media promote."<ref name="teenhollywood">{{cite news |publisher=TeenHollywood |title=Johannson Disgusted With Hollywood Attitude To Weight |url=http://www.teenhollywood.com/d.asp?r=132356&c=1055 |date=September 15, 2006 |accessdate=September 15, 2006}}</ref>

About her religious affiliation, Johansson described herself as Jewish when she was talking about Woody Allen: "I just adore Woody," she says. "We have a lot in common. We're New Yorkers, Jewish. We have a very easygoing relationship."<ref name="usatoday807">{{cite news |last=Stinson |first=Jeffrey |title=Hollywood enters the era of Scarlett Johansson |url=http://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2007-08-21-scarlett-johansson-cover_N.htm |work=USA Today |date=August 22, 2007 |accessdate=September 19, 2007}}</ref> She celebrates a "little of both" referring to Christmas and [[Hanukkah]].<ref name="bangitout">{{cite web |work=BangItOut |title= Match Point (2005) |first=Jordan |last=Hiller |url=http://www.bangitout.com/reviews112.html |accessdate=July 18, 2006}}</ref> She has stated that she dislikes it when celebrities thank [[God]] or [[Jesus]] in their award acceptance speeches.<ref name="femfirst">{{cite news |publisher=FemaleFirst |title=Scarlett Johansson slams God acceptance speeches |url=http://www.femalefirst.co.uk/celebrity/Scarlett+Johansson-1929.html |accessdate=July 12, 2009}}</ref>

Johansson is a Global Ambassador for the aid and development agency, [[Oxfam]].<ref name="Oxfam">{{cite news |url=http://www.oxfam.org/en/news/ambassadors/scarlett_johansson |title=Scarlett Johansson, Oxfam Ambassador |archivedate=October 12, 2007 |publisher=Oxfam International |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20071012115042/http://oxfam.org/en/news/ambassadors/scarlett_johansson |date=2007-07 |accessdate=February 12, 2008}}</ref> In March 2008, a UK-based bidder paid [[pound sterling|<U+00A3>]]20,000 on an [[eBay]] auction to benefit Oxfam, winning a hair and makeup treatment, a pair of tickets and a chauffered trip to accompany Johansson on a 20-minute date to the world premiere of ''[[He's Just Not That into You (film)|He's Just Not That Into You]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7295871.stm |title=Fan pays <U+00A3>20,000 to date Scarlett |date=March 14, 2008 |accessdate=July 24, 2009 | work=BBC News}}</ref>

=== Political advocacy ===
Johansson is registered as an [[Independent (voter)|independent]]<ref name="T-IND">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/1577733/Scarlett-Johansson-supports-Barack-Obama.html|title=Scarlett Johansson supports Barack Obama|last=Elsworth|first=Catherine|date=February 5, 2008|publisher=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=9 May 2010 | location=London}}</ref> and campaigned for [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic candidate]] [[John Kerry]] in the [[United States presidential election, 2004|2004 United States presidential election]].<ref name="localfav" /> About [[George W. Bush]]'s reelection, she said, "[I am] disappointed. I think it was a disappointment for a large percentage of the population."<ref name="cmusic2">{{cite news | title=Johansson: Americans disappointed by Bush's re-election |publisher=ContactMusic |url=http://www.contactmusic.com/new/xmlfeed.nsf/mndwebpages/johansson%20americans%20disappointed%20by%20bushs%20re-election |date=August 23, 2005 |accessdate=July 18, 2006}}</ref> Johansson also campaigned for Democratic candidate [[Barack Obama]]:<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.usatoday.com/life/people/2008-01-30-celebrity-politics_N.htm |title=Primary time for celebs: Star power floods political arena |work=[[USA Today]] |date=January 30, 2008 |accessdate=July 25, 2009 | first=Gary | last=Strauss}}</ref> her efforts included appearances in [[Iowa]] during January 2008, where her efforts were targeted at younger voters;<ref name="DTKJ">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2008/01/15/politics/uwire/main3718699.shtml|title=Impact Of Student Voters Questioned|last=Johnson|first=Katelyn|date=January 15, 2008|publisher=[[Daily Trojan]]|accessdate=9 May 2010}}</ref> an appearance at [[Cornell College]]; <ref>{{cite news |title=Political discourse is too one-sided |work=The Cornellian |volume=129 |issue=2 |accessdate=July 25, 2009 |url=http://www.thecornellian.com/archives/viewarticle.php?viewID=1010}}</ref> and a speaking engagement at [[Carleton College]], in [[Northfield, Minnesota|Northfield]], [[Minnesota]], on [[Super Tuesday, 2008]].<ref name="MIND">{{cite web|url=http://minnesotaindependent.com/3082/scarlett-johansson-sprinkles-a-little-stardust-at-carleton|title=Scarlett Johansson sprinkles a little stardust at Carleton|last=Fecke|first=Jeff|date=February 5, 2008|publisher=[[Minnesota Independent]]|accessdate=20 Jul 2010}}</ref> Johansson appeared in the 2008 music video for [[Black Eyed Peas]] front man [[Will.i.am]]'s song, "[[Yes We Can]]", directed by [[Jesse Dylan]], a song inspired by Obama's speech following the [[New Hampshire primary, 2008|2008 New Hampshire primary]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKN0519585420080207 |title=Musicians rock for Barack on Super Tuesday |publisher=Reuters |date=February 5, 2008 |accessdate=July 25, 2009}}</ref> In addition to her political advocacy, Johansson has taken part in social advocacy as part of the anti-poverty campaign [[ONE Campaign|ONE]] which was organized by [[U2]] lead singer [[Bono]].<ref name="localfav" />

